<h1>Working with Launches</h1>

<p>Launches are Service Catalog product provisioning operations that allow you to deploy standardized products across multiple AWS accounts and regions.</p>

<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>The launches action type allows you to:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Provision Service Catalog products from shared portfolios</li>
  <li>Update existing provisioned products when parameters change</li>
  <li>Terminate provisioned products when no longer needed</li>
  <li>Handle cross-account product sharing and provisioning</li>
  <li>Support both hub and spoke execution modes</li>
</ul>

<h2>Launch Configuration</h2>

<p>To configure a launch in your manifest, you need to specify:</p>

<h3>Required Parameters</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>launch_name</strong>: Unique name for the provisioned product</li>
  <li><strong>portfolio</strong>: Name of the Service Catalog portfolio</li>
  <li><strong>product</strong>: Name of the product to provision</li>
  <li><strong>version</strong>: Version of the product to deploy</li>
  <li><strong>region</strong>: AWS region for deployment</li>
  <li><strong>account_id</strong>: Target AWS account ID</li>
  <li><strong>execution</strong>: Execution mode (hub or spoke)</li>
</ul>

<h3>Optional Parameters</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>parameters</strong>: Product launch parameters</li>
  <li><strong>ssm_param_inputs</strong>: SSM parameters to retrieve for input</li>
  <li><strong>tags</strong>: Tags to apply to the provisioned product</li>
  <li><strong>retry_count</strong>: Number of retry attempts</li>
  <li><strong>worker_timeout</strong>: Timeout for the task</li>
  <li><strong>requested_priority</strong>: Task priority</li>
</ul>

<h2>Example Configuration</h2>

<pre><code class="language-yaml">launches:
  my-application:
    portfolio: shared-services
    product: web-application
    version: v1.2.0
    parameters:
      InstanceType: t3.medium
      Environment: production
    deploy_to:
      tags:
        - regions: us-east-1
          accounts:
            - "123456789012"
</code></pre>

<h2>Launch Lifecycle</h2>

<h3>Provisioning</h3>
<p>When a launch is first executed, Cloud Workflow Engine will:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Check if a provisioned product with the launch name already exists</li>
  <li>If not, create a new provisioned product with the specified parameters</li>
  <li>If exists, compare parameters and update if they have changed</li>
  <li>Skip provisioning if parameters are unchanged</li>
</ol>

<h3>Parameter Updates</h3>
<p>When parameters change, the existing provisioned product is updated rather than recreated, preserving resource continuity where possible.</p>

<h3>Termination</h3>
<p>Provisioned products can be terminated by removing them from the manifest or using the terminate action.</p>

<h2>Best Practices</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Use descriptive launch names that indicate the purpose and environment</li>
  <li>Version your products to ensure consistent deployments</li>
  <li>Use SSM parameters for sensitive or dynamic values</li>
  <li>Tag launches appropriately for cost tracking and organization</li>
  <li>Test product updates in development environments first</li>
  <li>Document parameter requirements and defaults</li>
</ul>

